'''Cindy Lou Hensley McCain''' (born May 20, 1954<ref name="trib-bio">{{cite news | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/politics/chi-041408-cindy-mccain-bio,1,2151434.story | title=Bio of Cindy Hensley McCain | publisher=''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' | date=2008-04-15 | accessdate=2008-04-22}}</ref>) is an [[United States|American]] [[businessperson]] and [[philanthropist]], and the wife of [[United States Senator]] and 2000 and 2008 [[presidential candidate]] [[John McCain]] of [[Arizona]]. She is [[Chair (official)|chair]] of [[Hensley & Co.]],<ref name="hensley">{{cite web | url=http://www.abwholesaler.com/hensley/AboutUs/Contacts | title=About Us: Our People | publisher=[[Hensley & Co.]] | accessdate=2006-11-14}}</ref><ref name="yahoo profile">{{cite web | url=http://biz.yahoo.com/ic/121/121680.html | title=Hensley & Company Company Profile | publisher=[[Yahoo! Finance]] | accessdate=2008-01-11}}</ref> founded by [[Jim Hensley|her father]] and one of the largest [[Anheuser-Busch]] beer distributors in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abwholesaler.com/hensley/AboutUs/AboutUs |title=About Hensley |accessdate=2008-07-08 |publisher=[[Hensley & Co.]]}}</ref>  

She founded and ran a non-profit organization, the American Voluntary Medical Team, from 1988 to 1995 that organized trips by medical personnel to disaster-struck or war-torn third-world areas.  She continues to be an active philanthropist and serves on the boards of several charitable organizations.

==Early life and education==
Cindy Lou Hensley was born in [[Phoenix, Arizona]],<ref name="aas030908"/> to [[Jim Hensley|James Hensley]], who founded [[Hensley & Co.]] in 1955,<ref name="yahoo profile"/> and Marguerite "Smitty" Hensley (n<U+00E9>e Johnson).<ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/22/AR2006102201228.html "Sen. John McCain's mother-in-law dies"], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', [[October 22]], [[2006]] (URL last accessed November 14, 2006).</ref><ref name="aas030908">{{cite news | url=http://www.statesman.com/news/content/news/stories/nation/03/09/0309cindymccain.html | title=As candidate's wife, Cindy McCain finds herself in spotlight | author=Bob Dart | publisher=''[[Austin American-Statesman]]'' | date=2008-03-09 | accessdate=2008-03-26}}</ref><ref name="wargs1">{{cite web|url=http://www.wargs.com/political/hensley.html |title=Ancestry of Cindy McCain |accessdate=2008-07-05 |publisher=wargs.com }}</ref>  She was raised as the only child of her parents' second marriages<ref name="usa-10">{{cite news | url=http://www.usnews.com/articles/news/national/2007/12/05/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-cindy-mccain.html | title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Cindy McCain | author= Bobbie Kyle | publisher=''[[USA Today]]'' | date=2008-01-11 | accessdate=2008-01-11}}</ref> and grew up on Phoenix's [[Central Avenue, Phoenix, Arizona|North Central Avenue]] in affluent circumstances.<ref name="salon-tapper"/><ref name="Scheiber"/><ref name="nykr-levy">{{cite news | url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2008/09/15/080915fa_fact_levy | title=The Lonesome Trail | author=[[Ariel Levy|Levy, Ariel]] | publisher=''[[The New Yorker]]'' | date=2008-09-15 | accessdate=2008-09-10}}</ref>  (Dixie L. Burd, who is the daughter of Marguerite Smith through a prior relationship, is her half-sister,<ref name=Argetsinger-Roberts>{{cite news|author=Argetsinger, Amy and Roberts, Roxanne|title=Sibling Revelation: An Overlooked Branch of Cindy McCain's Family Tree|date=[[August 20]], [[2008]]|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/20/AR2008082000253_pf.html|publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]''|accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref> as is Kathleen Hensely Portalski, daughter of Jim Hensley and his first wife, Mary Jeanne Parks.<ref name=Argetsinger-Roberts /><ref name="npr081808">Ted Robbins, (August 18, 2008)  [http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=93708729 "Cindy McCain's Half Sister 'Angry' She's Hidden"], [[National Public Radio]]. Accessed August 18, 2008.</ref>)  Cindy Hensley was named [[rodeo queen|Junior Rodeo Queen of Arizona]] in 1968.<ref name="nw063008">{{cite news | url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/142650/ | title=In Search of Cindy McCain | author=Holly Bailey | publisher=''[[Newsweek]]'' | date=2008-06-30 | accessdate=2008-06-23}}</ref><ref name="nyt062907">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/29/us/politics/29cindy.html | title=Mrs. McCain Is Speaking Up in a Steely Tone | author=Jennifer Steinhauer | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2007-06-29 | accessdate=2008-01-12}}</ref> She went to [[Central High School (Phoenix, Arizona)|Central High School]]<ref name="usa-10"/> in Phoenix, where she was named Best Dressed  as a senior and graduated in 1972.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.centralhighalumni.org/Newsletters/October2003.pdf | publisher=Central High Alumni' Echoes | title=Association announces honorary co-chairs | date=October-November 2003 | accessdate=2008-01-11|format=PDF}}</ref><ref name="nykr-levy"/>

Hensley received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in [[education]] from the [[University of Southern California]],<ref name="trib-bio"/><ref name="mcc2008-bio">{{cite web | url=http://www.exploremccain.com/About/CindyBio.htm | title=About Cindy McCain | publisher=John McCain 2008 | accessdate=2008-01-11}}</ref> where she was a [[cheerleader]]<!--Talk readers have doubted this, be on lookout for confirmation or refutation--><ref name="ct041508"/><ref name="nw063008"/>{{dubious}} and joined the socially conservative [[Kappa Alpha Theta]] sorority as a freshman.<ref name="Scheiber">{{cite news | url=http://www.tnr.com/politics/story.html?id=0fd7470d-a41f-4d9e-9328-fd079b476a0a | title=Made Man | author=Scheiber, Noam | publisher=''[[The New Republic]]'' | date=2008-08-20 | accessdate=2008-08-22}}</ref><ref>[http://www.usctheta.org/famous.php "Famous Thetas"], Kappa Alpha Theta, Omicron Chapter, University of Southern California.  Retrieved [[2008-02-08]].</ref>  She continued on at USC, and received a [[Master of Arts (postgraduate)|Master of Arts]] in [[special education]] in 1978.<ref name="trib-bio"/><ref name="nykr-levy"/>  There she participated in a movement [[therapy]] pilot program that laid the way for a standard treatment for children with severe disabilities;<ref name="mcc2008-bio"/> she published the work ''Movement Therapy: A Possible Approach'' in 1978.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0-uxIAAACAAJ&dq=%22movement+therapy%22+%22cindy+lou+hensley%22 | title=Movement Therapy: A Possible Approach | last=Hensley | first=Cindy Lou | publisher=[[University of Southern California]] | year=1978 | id=Order number 2576H}}</ref>  Declining a role in the family business,<ref name="nyt030200"/> she worked for a year as a special education teacher working with children with [[Down syndrome]] and other disabilities at [[Agua Fria High School]] in [[Avondale, Arizona]].<ref name="mcc2008-bio"/><ref name="aas030908"/><ref name="nw063008"/><ref name="nykr-levy"/>

==Marriage and family==
[[Image:Bath3.JPG|thumb|Cindy McCain, at christening of [[USS John S. McCain (DDG-56)|USS ''John S. McCain'']], September 1992, with daughter [[Meghan McCain|Meghan]], son Jack, and husband John at the [[Bath Iron Works]] shipyard, [[Bath, Maine]].]]
Hensley met [[John McCain]] in April 1979 at a military reception in [[Hawaii]].<ref name="Kristof">{{cite news
|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B02EFDF1439F934A15751C0A9669C8B63
|title= P.O.W. to Power Broker, A Chapter Most Telling
|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''
|date=[[February 27]], [[2000]] |author=[[Nicholas Kristof]]
|accessdate=2007-04-22}}</ref>  He was the [[U.S. Navy]] [[liaison]] officer to the [[United States Senate]], almost eighteen years her senior.<ref name="bazaar"/>  McCain and Hensley quickly began a relationship,<ref name="bazaar">{{cite news | url=http://www.harpersbazaar.com/magazine/feature-articles/cindy-mccain-0707 | title=Cindy McCain: Myth vs. Reality | author=Nancy Collins | publisher=''[[Harpers Bazaar]]'' | month=July | year=2007 | accessdate=2008-01-11}}</ref> traveling between Arizona and Washington to see each other.<ref name="nw063008"/>  John McCain pushed to end his marriage of fourteen years;<ref name="Kristof" /> [[Carol McCain]] and John McCain stopped cohabiting in January 1980,<ref name="lat071108">{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nationworld/nation/la-na-divorce11-2008jul11,0,6546861.story | title=McCain's broken marriage and fractured Reagan friendship | author=Serrano, Richard A.; Vartabedian, Ralph | publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' | date=2008-07-11 | accessdate=2008-07-11}}</ref> and Carol accepted a divorce in February 1980,<ref name="Kristof" /> effective in April 1980.  John and Cindy were married on May 17, 1980 at the [[Arizona Biltmore Hotel]] in Phoenix.<ref name="nw063008"/>  They made a [[prenuptial agreement]] that kept most of her family's assets under her name;<ref name="ap041808"/> they have since kept their finances apart and file separate [[Tax return (United States)|income tax returns]].<ref name="ap041808">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2008/04/18/politics/main4027276.shtml | title=McCain Releases His Tax Returns | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for [[CBS News]] | date=2008-04-18 | accessdate=2008-04-24}}</ref>

Her father's business and political contacts helped gain her husband a foothold in Arizona politics.<ref name="Kristof"/> She campaigned with her husband door-to-door during his successful first bid for [[U.S. Congress]] in 1982,<ref name="nyt062907"/> and was heavily involved in campaign strategy.<ref name="Scheiber"/> Her wealth from an expired [[Trust law|trust]] from her parents provided significant loans to the campaign<ref name="az-arizona">{{cite news |url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/specials/mccain/articles/0301mccainbio-chapter5.html |title=John McCain Report: Arizona, the early years |author=Dan Nowicki, [[Bill Muller]] |publisher=''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' |date=2007-03-01 |accessdate=2007-11-21}}</ref><ref>Bill Muller, [http://web.archive.org/web/20011212225613/http://www.arizonarepublic.com/special39/articles/1003mccainbook4.html <U+201C>Chapter IV: Arizona, the early years<U+201D>], The Arizona Republic ([[1999-06-05]]), via Archive.org: <U+201C>In 1982....the McCains lent $169,000 of their own money to the campaign....In the end, including the personal loans, McCain would raise more than $550,000 to win the seat.<U+201D></ref><ref name=Frantz>Frantz, Douglas, [http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0E14FC3F540C728EDDAB0894D8404482&n=Top%2fReference%2fTimes%20Topics%2fSubjects%2fP%2fPresidents%20and%20Presidency%20%28US%29 "A Beer Baron and a Powerful Publisher Put McCain on a Political Path"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', pp. A14, [[February 21]], [[2000]], URL retrieved [[November 29]], [[2006]].  "Though he had little money of his own because he had been a career naval officer, his wife's fortune allowed him to lend $167,000 to the campaign, which was permissible under campaign laws then."</ref> and helped it survive a period of early debt.<ref name="ap040308">{{cite news | url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/23930780/ | title=Beer heiress could be next first lady | author=Sharon Theimer | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for [[MSNBC.com]] | date=2008-04-03 | accessdate=2008-04-29}}</ref>  

Once he was elected, the couple moved to [[Alexandria, Virginia]].<ref name="wapo030200">{{cite news | url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/50640248.html?dids=50640248:50640248&FMT=FT&FMTS=ABS:FT&fmac=&date=Mar+2%2C+2000&author=Lois+Romano&desc=Out+of+the+Fire%2C+Politics+Calls%3B+Ex-POW+Turns+Washington+Insider | title=Out of the Fire, Politics Calls; Ex-POW Turns Washington Insider | author=Romano, Lois | publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' | date=2000-03-02}}</ref>  She spent two months in late 1983 writing handwritten notes on over 4,000 [[Christmas cards]] to be sent to constituents and others.<ref name="wapo030200"/>  She was an outsider who was snubbed by the Washington congressional social scene, in part because Carol McCain was a popular figure in town,<ref name="nyt101708c">{{cite news | url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/10/18/us/politics/18cindy.html | title=Behind McCain, Outsider in Capital Wanting Back In | author=Kantor, Jodi and Halbfinger, David M. | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2008-10-17 | accessdate=2008-10-18}}</ref> and she grew homesick for Arizona.<ref name="wapo030200"/><ref name="nw063008"/>  She suffered several [[miscarriage]]s.<ref name="bazaar"/><ref name="nw063008"/>

She moved back to Arizona in early 1984,<ref name="nw063008"/> and gave birth to her child, Meghan, later that year.<ref name="nw063008"/>  She subsequently had John Sidney IV (known as "Jack") (born 1986) and James (known as "Jimmy") (born 1988).<ref name="nyt-bio">{{cite web | url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/john_mccain/index.html | title=John McCain | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | accessdate=2008-03-28}}</ref>  [[#Adoption|Their fourth child, Bridget, was adopted in 1991]]. <!-- Should Cindy also be labeled a stepmother to McCain's children Doug, Andy, and Sidney from his first marriage?  They were 20, 18, and 14 years old at the time of the second marriage, and when children are 18 and over the term is not usually used (see [[Stepfamily]] article).  It is not clear where Sidney, the youngest, lived but the Kristof NYT article suggests with her mother, in which case Cindy may also have not been a stepmother in any real sense. -->  Her parents lived across the street and helped her raise the children while her husband was frequently in Washington;<ref name="bazaar"/> she typically only saw him on weekends.<ref name="nw063008"/>  She organized elaborate fundraisers for him and expanded their home.<ref name="nyt101708c"/>

In April 1986, she and her father invested $359,100 in a shopping center project with Phoenix banker [[Charles Keating]].<ref name="nw063008"/> This, combined with her role as a bookkeeper who later had difficulty finding receipts for family trips on Keating's jet,<ref name="nyt030200">{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D01E4D61F39F930A35750C0A9669C8B63 | title=Unexpectedly, Cindy McCain Basks in a New Political Role | author=Melinda Henneberger | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2000-03-02 | accessdate=2008-01-12}}</ref> caused complications for her husband during the [[Keating Five]] scandal, when he was being examined for his role regarding oversight of Keating's bank.<ref name="nw063008"/>

==American Voluntary Medical Team==
===Founding and mission===
In 1988, inspired by a vacation visit four years earlier to substandard medical facilities on [[Truk Lagoon]],<ref name="ct041508">{{cite news | url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/politics/chi-041408-cindy-mccain,1,5025892,full.story | title=The contrasts of Cindy McCain | author=Jill Zuckman | publisher=''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' | date=2008-04-15 | accessdate=2008-04-23}}</ref><ref name="nw063008"/> Cindy McCain founded the American Voluntary Medical Team (AVMT).<ref name="trib-bio"/>  It was a [[non-profit organization]] that organized trips for doctors, nurses, and other medical personnel to provide [[Mobile Army Surgical Hospital|MASH]]-like emergency medical care to disaster-struck or war-torn third-world areas such as [[Micronesia]], [[Vietnam]] (before relations were normalized between them and the U.S.<ref name="ct041508"/>), [[Kuwait]] (arriving five days after the conclusion of the [[Gulf War]]<ref name="ct041508"/>), [[Zaire]] (to help refuges from the [[Rwandan genocide]]<ref name="nyt101708c"/>), [[Iraq]], [[Nicaragua]], [[India]], [[Bangladesh]] and [[El Salvador]].<ref name="salon-tapper"/><ref name="care"/><ref name="one-life"/><ref name="alexander">{{cite book |title = Man of the People: The Life of John McCain |first = Paul |last = Alexander |authorlink=Paul Alexander |url= |id = ISBN 0-471-22829-X |year = 2002 |publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons]]|pages=p. 163}}</ref><ref name="timberg-bio">Timberg, ''An American Odyssey'', pp. 180<U+2013>181.</ref> She led 55 of these missions over the next seven years,<ref name="mcc2008-bio"/> with each being of at least two weeks' duration.<ref name="timberg-bio"/>  AVMT also supplied treatment to poor sick children around the world.<ref name="feinberg">{{cite book |last=Feinberg |first=Barbara Silberdick |title=John McCain: Serving His Country |publisher=[[Millbrook Press]] |year=2000 |isbn=0761319743}} p. 35.</ref>  In 1993, Cindy McCain and the AVMT were honored with an award from [[Food for the Hungry]].<ref name="salon-tapper"/>

===Adoption===
While  at [[Mother Teresa]]'s [[orphanage]] in [[Dhaka, Bangladesh]], in 1991 <U+2014> as part of AVMT's assistance team following the [[1991 Bangladesh cyclone]]<ref name="one-life">{{cite book | last=McCain | first=Cindy Hensley | coauthors=Gina Bridgeman |  chapter=One Life at a Time | title=A Second Chicken Soup for the Woman's Soul: 101 More Stories | editor=Canfield, Hansen, Hawthorne, Shimoff | publisher=[[Counselor_magazine#Parent_company:_Health_Communications|Health Communications, Inc.]]| year=1998 | isbn=1558746218}}</ref> <U+2014> she met two infant girls she decided needed to be brought to the United States for medical treatment.<ref name="bazaar"/> She decided to adopt one of the girls (her husband readily agreeing), later named Bridget,<ref name="salon-tapper"/> and helped coordinate the adoption of the other little girl, named Mickey, for Wes Gullett, a family friend.<ref name="salon-tapper"/>

===Prescription drug addiction===
In 1989, Cindy McCain became addicted to [[Percocet]] and [[Vicodin]], [[opioid]] [[painkillers]], which she initially took to alleviate pain following two spinal surgeries for [[Spinal disc herniation|ruptured discs]], and to ease emotional stress during the [[Keating Five|Keating Five affair]].<ref name="wapo091208"/><ref name="az-rebound"/><ref name="az-rebound">{{cite news |url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/specials/mccain/articles/0301mccainbio-chapter8.html |title=John McCain Report: Overcoming scandal, moving on |author=Dan Nowicki, Bill Muller |publisher=''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' |date=2007-03-01 |accessdate=2007-11-23}}</ref><ref name="cnn112299">{{cite news | url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/11/22/cindy.mccain/index.html | title=Cindy McCain stays on an even keel | author=Bill Delaney | publisher=[[CNN.com]] | date=1999-11-22 | accessdate=2008-01-12}}</ref><ref name="alexander-more"/>  The addiction progressed to where she was taking upwards of twenty pills a day,<ref name="nw063008"/> and she resorted to having an AVMT physician write illegal prescriptions in the names of three AVMT employees without their knowledge.<ref name="wapo091208"/><ref name="Alexander"> {{cite book
 | last = Alexander 
 | first = Paul
 | authorlink = Paul Alexander
 | title = Man of the People: The Life of John McCain
 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=yL60SByrfcUC&pg=PA164&lpg=PA164&dq=gosinski+mccain&source=web&ots=1ODCZV-Kmn&sig=P9PwG12-gibKvy9KaFw-ATnoqOM&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=40&ct=result#PPA163,M1
 | accessdate = 2008-07-25
 | date = 2004-01-19
 | publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]]
 | isbn = 0471475459
 | pages = pp. 162-166
 }}</ref>  In 1992, her parents staged an [[Intervention (counseling)|intervention]] to force her to get help;<ref name="nyt030200"/> she told her husband about her problem, attended a drug treatment facility, began outpatient sessions, and ended her three years of addiction.<ref name="az-rebound"/>  Surgery in 1993 resolved her back pain.<ref name="az-rebound"/><ref name="alexander-more"/>  

In January 1993, Tom Gosinski, an AVMT employee who had discovered her illegal drug use, was terminated on budgetary grounds.<ref name="salon-silverman">Silverman, Amy, [http://www.salon.com/news/feature/1999/10/18/drugs/ "How Cindy McCain was outed for drug addiction"], ''[[Salon.com]]'', [[October 18]], [[1999]] (URL last accessed September 15, 2007).</ref>  Subsequently, he tipped off the [[Drug Enforcement Administration]], and a federal investigation ensued.<ref name="wapo091208"/><ref name="salon-silverman"/> McCain's defense team, led by John McCain's Keating Five lawyer [[John M. Dowd|John Dowd]], secured an agreement with the [[U.S. Attorney]]'s office for McCain, a first-time offender, that avoided charges while requiring her to pay financial restitution, enroll in a [[diversion program]] and do [[community service]].<ref name="wapo091208"/><ref name="salon-tapper"/><ref name="salon-silverman"/> Meanwhile, in early 1994 Gosinski filed a [[wrongful termination]] lawsuit against McCain, which he told her he would settle for $250,000.<ref name="wapo091208"/><ref name="salon-silverman"/>  In response, Dowd characterized this request as blackmail and requested that officials investigate Gosinski for [[extortion]].<ref name="wapo091208"/><ref name="salon-silverman"/> In the end, both Gosinski's lawsuit and the extortion investigation against him were dropped.<ref name="wapo091208"/><ref name="az-rebound"/>  

Knowing that the DEA prosecutors were about to publicly disclose her past addiction, McCain preemptively revealed the story to reporters saying she was doing so willingly: "Although my conduct did not result in compromising any missions of AVMT, my actions were wrong, and I regret them."<ref name="wapo091208"/><ref name="az-rebound"/><ref name="salon-tapper">[[Jake Tapper|Tapper, Jake]], [http://dir.salon.com/story/news/feature/1999/07/02/hillary/index.html?pn=3 "I'm not Hillary"], ''[[Salon.com]]'', [[July 2]], [[1999]] (URL last accessed April 4, 2007).</ref>

===Aftermath===
AVMT concluded its activities in 1995 in the wake of the McCain narcotics prescriptions controversy.<ref name="care"/><ref name="wapo091208">{{cite news | url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/09/11/AR2008091103928.html | title=A Tangled Story of Addiction | author=Kindy, Kimberly | publisher=''[[The Washington Post]]'' | date=2008-09-12 | accessdate=2008-09-12}}</ref>  That year, McCain founded a new organization, the [[Hensley Family Foundation]], which donates monies towards children's programs in Arizona and nationally,<ref name="salon-tapper"/> and she was largely a [[stay-at-home mom]] during the balance of the 1990s.<ref name="nyt030200"/>  She also held positions as vice president, director, and vice chair of Hensley & Co.<ref name="ap040308"/><ref name=Frantz/>

==Role in 2000 presidential campaign==
Although wary of the media,<ref name="salon-tapper"/> McCain was active in her husband's eventually unsuccessful [[John McCain presidential campaign, 2000|campaign for President of the United States in 2000]].<ref name="nyt030200"/>  She mostly provided good cheer, without discussing her opinions about national policy.  She impressed Republican voters with her elegance at coffee shops and other small campaign settings, where she frequently referred to her children, carpooling, and charity work.<ref name="nyt062907"/>  

She was upset by the notorious smear tactics<ref name="az-2000">{{cite news |url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/specials/mccain/articles/0301mccainbio-chapter10.html |title=John McCain Report: The 'maverick' runs |author=Dan Nowicki, Bill Muller |publisher=''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' |date=2007-03-01 |accessdate=2007-12-27}}</ref><ref name="nyt101907">{{cite news |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/19/us/politics/19mccain.html |title=Confronting Ghosts of 2000 in South Carolina |author=Jennifer Steinhauer |publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |date=2007-10-19 |accessdate=2008-01-07}}</ref> against her husband in the [[South Carolina primary]] that year, which included allegations involving her adopted daughter Bridget that she found "despicable".<ref name="nyt030200"/> Cindy McCain eventually forgave those responsible.<ref name="nyt062907"/>  She was chosen as the chair of the Arizona delegation to the [[2000 Republican National Convention]].<ref name="mcc2008-bio"/>

==Between presidential campaigns==
[[Image:John McCain and Cindy Naval Sea Cadet Corps graduation cropped.jpg|thumb|left|John and Cindy McCain at a [[United States Naval Sea Cadet Corps|Naval Sea Cadet Corps]] graduation, [[Fort Dix]], [[New Jersey]], July 2001.]]

In 2000, she became [[Chair (official)|chair]] of the now $300-million-a-year [[Hensley & Co.]]<ref name="abc052507">{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/Politics/Story?id=3213349&page=1 | title=Cindy McCain's Straight Talk | author=Jennifer Rubin | publisher=[[ABC News]] | date=2007-05-25 | accessdate=2008-01-12}}</ref> following her father's death.<ref name="alexander-more">{{cite news | url=http://www.more.com/more/story.jsp?storyid=/templatedata/more/story/data/1187029206605.xml | title=Cindy McCain at Full Throttle | author=[[Paul Alexander]] | publisher=''[[More (magazine)|More]]'' | month=September | year=2007 | accessdate=2008-01-30}}</ref>  She, her children, and one of John McCain's children from his first marriage own 68&nbsp;percent of the company.<ref name="lat062208">{{cite news | url=http://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-na-hensley22-2008jun22,0,3931241,full.story | title=McCain could have a conflict brewing | author=Ralph Vartabedian | publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' | date=2008-06-22 | accessdate=2008-06-23}}</ref>  As chair, her role takes the form of consultations with the company CEO on major initiatives such as new products, new plants, or employee welfare, rather than of an active physical presence;<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/election/special3/articles/0123biz-hensley.html | title=McCain, his wealth tied to wife's family beer business | author=Dawn Gilbertson | publisher=''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' | date=2007-01-23 | accessdate=2008-03-06}}</ref><ref name="sdm0807"/> she does not have operational control of Hensley, and Anheuser-Busch considers her to be an absentee owner.<ref name=Halbfinger /> By 2007, she had an annual income of over $400,000 from Hensley and an estimated net worth of $100 million.<ref name="ap041808"/>  She also owned at least $2.7 million worth of shares of Anheuser-Busch stock.<ref name="bloom061308">{{cite news | url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=aJik4WI9a0M8&refer=us | title=Cindy McCain May Reap Benefits of Anheuser-Busch Bid | author=Jonathan D. Salant, Kristin Jensen | publisher=[[Bloomberg News]] | date=2008-06-13 | accessdate=2008-06-26}}</ref><ref name=Halbfinger>{{cite news|author=Halbfinger, David M.|title=For McCains, a Public Path but Private Wealth|date=[[August 22]], [[2008]]|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/23/us/politics/23mccain.html|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref>  With her children, she owns a minority stake in the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]] baseball team.<ref name="ap040308"/>  

She became actively involved with [[Operation Smile]] in 2001,<ref name="smile">{{cite press release | url=http://www.operationsmile.com/docs/pr20050912.pdf | title=Operation Smile to Honor Cindy McCain, ... | publisher=[[Operation Smile]] | date=[[2005-09-12]] | accessdate=2008-01-12|format=PDF}}</ref> taking parts in its trips to [[Morocco]], [[Vietnam]], and [[India]].<ref name="smile"/>  She was honored by the organization in 2005,<ref name="smile"/> and sits on its [[board of directors]].<ref name="care"/>
She joined the board of directors of [[CARE (relief)|CARE]] in 2005.<ref name="care">[http://www.care.org/about/boardbios.asp?id=13 "CARE Board Member Biography: Cindy Hensley McCain"], [[CARE (relief)|CARE]] website, URL last accessed November 14, 2006.</ref> She is on the board of the [[HALO Trust]],<ref name="care"/> and has visited operations to remove [[landmine]]s in [[Cambodia]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Mozambique]], and [[Angola]].<ref name="mcc2008-bio"/>  She makes financial contributions to these organizations via her family trust<ref name="ct041508"/> and views her role as watching them in the field to ensure they are frugal and their money is being spent effectively.<ref name="sdm0807"/>  On occasion she has criticized foreign regimes on [[human rights]] grounds, such as [[Politics of Burma|Myanmar's military junta]].<ref name="ap061908">{{cite news | url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/25260004/ | title=Cindy McCain criticizes Myanmar's leaders | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for [[MSNBC]] | date=2008-06-19 | accessdate=2008-06-25}}</ref>

In April 2004 McCain suffered a near-fatal [[stroke]] caused by [[high blood pressure]],<ref>Villa, Judi, "Cindy McCain goes home; full recovery is expected", ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'', [[April 17]], [[2004]].</ref><ref name="alexander-more"/> although she was still able to attend some events.<ref name="nyt101708c"/>  After several months of physical therapy to overcome her leg and arm limitations, she made a mostly full recovery, although she still suffers from some [[short-term memory]] loss and difficulties in writing.<ref name="alexander-more"/>  She owns a home in [[Coronado, California]], next to the [[Hotel del Coronado]];<ref name="sdm0807">{{cite news | url=http://sandiegomagazine.com/media/San-Diego-Magazine/August-2007/Cindy-McCain/ | title=Cindy McCain | author=Tom Blair | publisher=''[[San Diego Magazine]]'' | month=August | year=2007 | accessdate=2008-03-08}}</ref> her family had vacationed in Coronado growing up, and she has gone there for recuperation and family get-togethers.<ref name="sdm0807"/>  She or her family owns other residential and commercial real estate in California, Arizona and Virginia<ref name="ap040308"/> and, including rental properties, McCain herself owns ten homes and part of three office complexes.<ref name=Halbfinger /><ref>Vogel, Kenneth. [http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0808/12700.html "McCain family owns 8 properties"], ''[[The Politico]]'' ([[2008-08-21]]). Retrieved [[2008-08-21]].</ref><ref name="nw070708">{{cite news | url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/143775/ | title=Mrs. McCain, San Diego County Would Like a Word | author=Suzanne Smalley, Andrew Murr, Mark Hosenball, Nathan Dinsdale | publisher=''[[Newsweek]]'' | date=2008-07-07 | accessdate=2008-07-01}}</ref>  She is an amateur [[aircraft pilot|pilot]] and [[race car driver]].<ref name="nw063008"/>

==Role in 2008 presidential campaign==
[[Image:John and Cindy McCain.jpg|thumb|right|John and Cindy McCain at a campaign stop, early February 2008]]
She has been active and visible in [[John McCain presidential campaign, 2008|her husband's presidential campaign during 2007 and 2008]],<ref name="nyt062907"/> returning to Arizona frequently to attend to domestic duties<ref name="sdm0807"/> and interrupting campaigning for her overseas charitable work.<ref name="ct041508"/><ref name="ap061908"/> She has preferred to travel with her husband and introduce him, rather than act as a campaign surrogate with a separate schedule.<ref>Baer, Susan. "[http://www.washingtonian.com/articles/people/9319.html Michelle Vs. Cindy]", ''[[Washingtonian]]'', September 1, 2008.</ref><ref name="nyt101708c"/>  In August 2008, a member of the public shook her hand very vigorously, aggravating her existing [[carpal tunnel syndrome]] condition and causing her to slightly sprain her wrist.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/uselection2008/johnmccain/2560797/Cindy-McCain-braves-campaign-handshake-strain.html|title=Cindy McCain braves campaign handshake strain |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''|date=2008-08-15|accessdate=2008-08-15}}</ref>

McCain has stated that the American public wants a [[First Lady of the United States]] who will tend toward a traditional role in that position.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/1213cindy1212.html | title=Cindy McCain: Caring, campaigning and coping | author=Richard Ruelas | publisher=''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' | date=2007-12-13 | accessdate=2008-01-12}}</ref>  She would not attend [[United States Cabinet|Cabinet]] meetings,<ref name="sdm0807"/> but would continue her involvement in overseas non-profit organizations and would urge Americans to do the same globally or locally;<ref name="sdm0807"/> she envisions herself as a possible figurehead for humanitarian work, along the lines of [[Diana, Princess of Wales]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/uselection2008/johnmccain/2195589/Cindy-McCain-'inspired-by-DIana'.html | title=Cindy McCain 'inspired by Diana' | publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' | date=2008-06-26 | accessdate=2008-06-26}}</ref>
[[Image:Cindy_at_White_House.JPG#Summary|thumb|left|Visiting [[George W. Bush|President Bush]] at the [[White House]] on March 5, 2008]]
She made statements critical of the [[George W. Bush administration|Bush administration]] for not deploying enough troops during the [[Iraq War]],<ref name="nyt062907"/> and was an internal critic within the McCain campaign of its profligate spending during the first part of 2007.<ref name="ct041508"/> In February 2008, McCain made news by being critical of [[Michelle Obama]], the wife of Democratic Presidential candidate [[Barack Obama]], who had said, "And let me tell you something: For the first time in my adult lifetime I am really proud of my country."  McCain replied:  "I am proud of my country. I don't know about you<U+2014>if you heard those words earlier<U+2014>I am very proud of my country."<ref>[http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/0219campaignwives0219-ON.html "Cindy McCain takes Michelle Obama to task"], ''Newsday'', February 19, 2008.</ref>  Also in February 2008, she publicly appeared beside her husband during a press conference in response to a [[John McCain lobbyist controversy|newspaper report regarding his connection to a lobbyist]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/2008-02-21-4187272820_x.htm | title=Cindy McCain, Like Others, Stands by Man | author=Libby Quaid | publisher=[[Associated Press]] | date=2008-02-21 | accessdate=2008-02-21}}</ref>

McCain has faced media scrutiny about her wealth, spending habits, and financial obligations.<ref name="nw070708"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/politics/20080701-9999-1m1mccain.html | title=McCain's wife avoids default on property taxes | author=Powell, Ronald W | publisher=''[[The San Diego Union-Tribune]]'' | date=2008-07-01 | accessdate=2008-07-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0708/11477.html | title=Cindy<U+2019>s fortune: An asset and a liability | author=Vogel, Kenneth P | publisher=''[[The Politico]]'' | date=2008-07-02 | accessdate=2008-07-02}}</ref> At first declining to release her separate income tax returns, saying it was a privacy issue and that she would not do so even if she became First Lady,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/politics/election2008/2008-05-08-cindy-mccain-taxes_N.htm | title=Cindy McCain: I'll never release my tax returns | publisher=[[Associated Press]] for ''[[USA Today]]'' | date=2008-05-08 | accessdate=2008-05-08}}</ref> she later released the first two pages of her 2006 return, which showed $6 million in income for that year (including nearly $570,000 in itemized deductions and more than $1.7 million paid in federal income taxes).<ref name=taxreturn>{{cite news |title=Cindy McCain had $6 million income in 2006|publisher=Associated Press |first=Jim |last=Kuhnhenn |date=2008-05-23|url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jb9uER4h4UdABR8_D9WgU4RPtriwD90RJKHO0|accessdate=2008-05-24}}</ref> The campaign has said that any decisions about how to handle her role in Hensley & Co. if she becomes First Lady would not be made until that time.<ref name="lat062208"/>  While she would gain a considerable profit from the agreed-upon acquisition of  Anheuser-Busch by the [[Belgium|Belgian]] company [[InBev]],<ref name="bloom061308"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9D06E2D8123AF936A25754C0A96E9C8B63 | title=Wife's Profit Worth a Toast | author=David M. Halbfinger | publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' | date=2008-07-15 | accessdate=2008-07-23}}</ref> she was initially under some political pressure to help oppose the deal and keep Anheuser-Busch under American ownership.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://thehill.com/campaign-2008/budweiser-deal-puts-political-pressure-on-mccain-campaign-2008-06-25.html | title=Budweiser deal puts political pressure on McCain campaign | author=Michael O<U+2019>Brien | publisher=''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'' | date=2008-06-25 | accessdate=2008-06-26}}</ref> 

[[Image:Cindy McCain speaks at RNC 2008.jpg|thumb|right|Cindy McCain speaks at the [[2008 Republican National Convention]].]]
In June 2008, a [[Rasmussen Reports]] poll found that 49&nbsp;percent of voters viewed Cindy McCain favorably and 29&nbsp;percent unfavorably,<ref>{{cite news | url=http://elections.foxnews.com/2008/06/11/michelle-obama-viewed-more-unfavorably-than-cindy-mccain-poll-finds/ | title=Michelle Obama Viewed More Unfavorably Than Cindy McCain, Poll Finds | publisher=[[Fox News]] | date=2008-06-11 | accessdate=2008-06-17}}</ref> while an [[ABC News]]/[[Washington Post]] poll found figures of 39&nbsp;percent and 25&nbsp;percent respectively.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://abcnews.go.com/PollingUnit/Vote2008/story?id=5185695&page=1 | title=Battle of the Spouses: A Bit Better for Obama | author=Gary Langer | publisher=[[ABC News]] | date=2008-06-18 | accessdate=2008-06-18}}</ref>  Her style and fashion sense have been the subject of much media scrutiny.<ref name="fashion">{{cite news|title=Fashion First|url=http://www.nypost.com/seven/06052008/entertainment/fashion/fashion_first_114025.htm|accessdate=2008-09-24|work=The New York Post|date=June 5, 2008|author=Callahan, Maureen}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[ABC News]]|title=Politics of Fashion: Styles of McCain, Obama, Palin|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=5725791&page=1|author=Fisher, Luchina|date=September 4, 2008|accessdate=2008-09-24}}</ref> McCain has been compared to former first lady [[Nancy Reagan]],<ref name="fashion"/> due to both her style and wardrobe<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.minnpost.com/stories/2008/09/04/3364/delegates_put_cindy_mccains_style_at_the_head_of_the_classy|title=Delegates put Cindy McCain's style at the head of the classy|accessdate=2008-09-24|date=September 4, 2008|work=MinnPost.com|author=Helms, Marissa}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,364467,00.html|title=Fashion Forward: Michelle Obama vs. Cindy McCain. Who's Got the Edge When It Comes to Style?|date=June 9, 2008|accessdate=2008-09-24|publisher=[[Fox News]]}}</ref> as well as demeanor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/us_and_americas/us_elections/article4214442.ece|title=Cindy McCain: Is John too old? Oh my gosh no, he wears me out|accessdate=2008-09-24|date=June 26, 2008|work=The Times|author=Macintyre, Ben}}</ref> Early in the campaign, some [[recipe]]s attributed to Cindy McCain turned out to be copied from other sources;<ref name="upi041508"/><ref>{{cite news|author=Suzanne Goldenberg|date=2008-04-16|publisher=''[[The Guardian]]''|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2008/apr/16/johnmccain.uselections2008|title=Recipes removed from McCain campaign website|accessdate=2008-05-01}} The recipes were for ahi tuna with Napa cabbage salad, crab scampi with whole wheat pasta, pasta with turkey sausage, and passion fruit mousse.</ref> the campaign attributed the problem to an error by an intern.<ref name="upi041508">{{cite news | url=http://www.upi.com/NewsTrack/Quirks/2008/04/15/upi_newstrack_quirks_in_the_news/9586/ | title=McCain site recipes really Food Network's | publisher=[[United Press International]] | date=2008-04-15 | accessdate=2008-04-15}}</ref>

Cindy McCain spoke on both the opening and final nights of the [[2008 Republican National Convention]] in early September 2008.  On the first night, truncated due to national attention regarding [[Hurricane Gustav]], she appeared with First Lady [[Laura Bush]] to deliver short remarks encouraging support for hurricane relief efforts along the [[United States Gulf Coast|Gulf Coast]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2008/POLITICS/09/01/rnc.gustav/?iref=hpmostpop|title= Laura Bush on Gustav: Americans 'are here to do what we can'|accessdate=2008-09-06|publisher=CNN|date=September 1, 2008}}</ref> and on the last night she introduced the seven McCain children and spoke about how her husband's love for his country had been passed on to them.<ref name="4speech">{{cite news|url=http://seattlepi.nwsource.com/national/1131ap_cvn_cindy_mccain.html?source=mypi|title=Cindy McCain praises husband as leader, father|author=DeMillo, Andrew|accessdate=2008-09-06|date=September 4, 2008|work=Seattle-Post Intelligencer}}</ref>  In October 2008, she increased the intensity of her public remarks against Obama's candidacy.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/jonathanmartin/1008/An_aggressive_Cindy_reprises_pride_in_country.html | title=An aggressive Cindy reprises pride in country | author=Martin, Jonathan | publisher=''[[The Politico]]'' | date=2008-10-17 | accessdate=2008-10-18}}</ref>

